EJECT

[[

James Joyce established the literary maxim that an author doesn't
have to explain what he wrote, and for a long time
I tried to emulate him.

Then I realized something.

I'm not James Joyce.

That statement could be read in several different ways,
primarily either as a cliche stating that I'm not that
good a writer, or that I'm just a different person,
and therefore a different writer, than James Joyce.
The double entendre is deliberate, and I try to
explain these things here, in my Author's Notes.

I wouldn't read them the first time through,
just enjoy the book, then read it again with the notes.
I'll try to provide PDF versions both with and without them.
]]

{{ I'll keep this novel about real people }}
{{ I'll not get lost in ivory towers }}
{{ I'll remember those who do the hard work }}
{{ I'll thank them for being so kind to me }}
{{ God I pray inspire this work }}
{{ Man I remind of its errors }}
{{ The Great American Novel it's not}}
{{ The Great anti-American one, maybe}}
{{ The Great Hawaiian novel, blalah?}}
{{ Da kine.}}

[[
"Those who do the hard work" was written when watching a Mexican friend
of mine butcher a cow, and his wife would always have a bowl of food for me,
the destitute gringo, thus "I'll thank them for being so kind to me".

I used to have a line in there: "this is a historical novel" to start
setting the stage for the key events that happen in the past - the
dot-com boom, 9/11, the _Columbia_ shuttle disaster

The novel toys throughout with the suggestion that it is, somehow,
maybe, or maybe not, the Great anti-American Novel.  So is it or isn't
it?  If it is anti-American, the novel itself takes a decidedly
tongue-in-cheeck approach to answering that question in the
affirmative.  A whole lot of ominous-sounding "requirements", half of which
turn out to be nothing more than sly little double entendres.  It really
depends on *your* definition what it is to be American!  Only then
can you decide if it is anti-American!

The novel also toys throughout with the idea of being "great",
starting right now on the first page.  Great how?  Great in what why?
If it ultimately sets off a successful Hawaiian revolution in real
life it *might* be regarded as the Great Hawaiian Novel!  Yet the
novel's answer comes on its last page, in its last sentence - it's
great because it's part of the Great Conversation (the allusion here
is to Mortimer Adler and the Great Books program); it's great because
it has something original to add to the Great Conversation, and what
is that?

Of course, "Christ is the answer", but that statement alone
wouldn't put in the Great Conversation, because it's been said
many times before.  Perhaps if I said it exceptionally well,
it'd garner some merit, but something more is needed to truly
add to the conversation.

How about "If you want to achieve a political revolution, a Hawaiian independence
bid makes more sense than flying to Mars"

but I feel that statement's aimed too personally at Elon Musk,
maybe with a "goofball!" thrown in at the end.

Maybe it's just "a secession/independence movement makes more
sense that any cockamamie scheme that will never work".

Or even "secession is a fundamental political right".

Maybe "capitalism is evil", but that's been said before, and in
better ways.  I'm not really hoping to convince my readers
that capitalism is evil, I expect that my supporters already
believe that and my opponents can't be swayed

Maybe "don't expand further into space; fix your problems on Earth instead"

Any way you read it, with the billionaire Elon Musk talking about
colonizing Mars in hopes of solving mankind's problems, this message
seems even more relevant now that when the first edition came out ten years
ago.
]]

EJECT


	    Requirements for The Great anti-American Novel

[[
Why write this crazy novel, and what are these ominous sounding requirements?

Well, I could just lay out my political and spritual program by writing
an essay that reads like I'm giving a speech, and I've done that before
in things like _My_Confession_ and the like.

This time I decided to aim for "high literature" and decided that the
book had to be some kind of scripted fiction that told some kind of
story wrapped around my ideas.  Some might
]]



T - 2693 days    leftists must be lazy

[[
This is STS-61, and the whole jamming the door shut on the Hubble
telescope scene is straight out of the wikipedia article.
It's Flight Day 4, December 6, 1993.

Readers who are really paying attention, now have a key to all
the dates in the novel.  In particular, neither 9/11 nor
the _Columbia_ disaster should come as any surprise to them.

Of course, I hope the reader notices that the time marker
on this scene predates "0 hour" by some time, and
juxtapose this with the futuristic setting of a spacewalk.

The first edition actually started on the second scene,
the super-hack.  This new opening scene was added to
enlarge the novel a bit (it was too short) and to
provide some more back story for Andrea Yeats.

2001 Mars Obyssey launched on April 7 (Julian 94), 2001, and arrived
on Mars 200 days later on October 24 (Julian 296).  A faster ship would have launched
faster and gotten there sooner.  Let's assume that the midpoint
of the mission would be the same day - Julian 195, July 21, 2001.

If we make May 21, 2001 their launch day (so it takes about four months to get to Mars),
they get there on September 21, 2001.

No, let's move everything up a month, to fit 9/11 in shortly after they arrive.

Launch on April 21, 2001 and arrive on August 21, 2001.

]]

"_Columbus_, Houston, for EVA."

[[
I hope Jeffrey Hoffman doesn't mind that I replaced him with crazy Andrea Yeats.

Is she crazy?  Her namesake sure is.  The "real" Andrea Yeats murdered
her five children in a bathtub, and explained the next day to a prison psychiatrist:

"It was the seventh deadly sin.  My children weren't richteous.  They stumpled
because I was evil.  The way I was raising them, they could never be saved.
Better for someone else to tie a millstone around their neck and cast
them in a river than stumble.  They were going to perish."

"I was so stupid!  Couldn't I have killed just one to fulfill the prophecy?
Couldn't I have offered Mary?"

"Are they in heaven?"

https://web.archive.org/web/20070902232526/http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/special/drownings/1268306.html

Also, get this - her husband was a former NASA engineer,
with a fundamentalist Christian streak that told him
to procreate as much as possible.  This went against medical advice
from family psychiatrists who warned both of them against
stopping her antipsychotic medication while carrying a child,
but he insisted, and she gave in.

So why don't I change the name?

First, the character has long been Andrea Yeats for many years before I knew of this story.

Changing the name doesn't seem right.

What's the point of changing the name?  To cover it up?

All of this needs to be disclosed!  These facts
go in the author's notes, not buried and dug up years
from now by some investigative reporter.

My detractors will leap onto the alarming similarities
beween a crazed Christian who murdered her children, the crazed Andrea Yeats who
gives away everything she owns, and the crazed author,
some nutcase Chrisitian communist
who imagines that he's "Eagle Six".

But here's the thing.

What happened to her children?

Ask any Christian minister what happened to Andrea Yeats' children.

They were aged 7, 5, 3, 2, and 6 months.

I'll bet most of them will tell you that they went to heaven.

And that she paid the ultimate penalty.

It seems brutally extreme to murder your children to ensure their salvation,
but if you're convinced that most people in the world are damned...

  It seems brutally extreme to murder office workers and military
  officers with hijacked jet planes, but if you think you're
  going to heaven as a martyr...

  It seems extreme to give everything away because some Bible verse
  (Luke 14:33) says you can't be a disciple otherwise,
  but if you believe the Bible is the inerrant Word of God...

  It seems extreme to keep praying to some imaginary God and trying
  to figure out what He wants you to do, but if you beleive that
  he's real...

Rabbits will kill their young.

When I was a boy, we kept pet rabbits in cages made of wire mesh, to
make it easier to collect their droppings.  As an adult, I am ashamed
of how we treated them, but I digress.  If a rabbit became pregnant,
we put straw in their cage so they could nest.  They would have
preferred straw all the time, so much so that when a female (was it Brownie?) became
pregnant unbeknownst to us, she killed her entire litter immediately
after birth by breaking their necks.

Andrea Yeats was diagnosed with psychosis.

Psychosis is, by definition, a loss of contact with reality.

When my psychiatrist friend told me that, I asked isn't
everyone psychotic, to some extent?

Could a religious experience like St. Francis's vision at
San Damiano be diagnosed as a psychotic episode?  Wouldn't an atheist
conclude that there is nothing else it could be?

Furthermore, the primary cause of psychosis is schizophrenia.

I have known two schizophrenics for long enough to conclude that
their voices are probably real and that they are possessed by demons.

Psychosis usually begins in early adulthood and affects approximately
three percent of the population!

I am personally part of that population.  When I was twenty-three years
old, I experienced a vision, as I described in _Bicycling_Across_America_.
Over the next twenty eight years, I've experienced at least another
half dozen similar experiences, and been in the presence of others
during their similar experiences at least twice.

The atheists believe I'm psychotic and I believe I've been touched by God.

I also believe that some portion of the psychotic population has been misdiagnosed
because their experiences are, in fact, real, either holy or demonic in origin, but real.

   I personally reject atheism, in part, because I find it impossible to
   beleive that what 30,000 people witnessed at Fatima was a mass
   hallucination, a mass psychotic episode, or anything of the kind.

Where does that leave me with Andrea Yeats?  Crazy?  Psychotic?

Who knows?
]]

Andrea finishing aligning the screwdriver with the bolt and pressed
the drive button.  She heard no sound but felt the vibration through
her gloved hand as she watched the bolt spin down, tighten, and lock.
Then she let go of the screwdriver and let it float away on its
tether.

[[
I have no idea what kinds of tools they had on that mission.

Do we really have "screwdrivers that require no torque to turn" (first
edition)?

Is that something you would actually use?  If you were floating
free yes, but probably not if your feet are tethered, as in this
scene.

A "mass spectrometer the size of a shoebox"?  Good grief, what for?
Sounds good, though, high-tech, it stays in.  Maybe I even
read about it somewhere.
]]

She was suspended by the side of an open access panel on the Hubbel
Space Telescope, her feet secured in a foot restraint, a $100,000 bag
of one-of-a-kind tools dangling in the vacuum next to her.
A screwdriver with an LCD
screen that displayed its torque and speed settings.  A mass
spectrometer the size of a shoebox.  Levered clamps custom designed to
insert and remove circuit panels of which no more than a dozen had
ever been manufactured.  Though she floated forty feet over the space
shuttle's open cargo bay, she had no fear of falling.  Had she
released her feet, she would only have drifted away gently, the
slight pressure from her foot pushing her up, away from the shuttle
bay, instead of down.

[[
Based on the pictures I've seen from space, I probably haven't imagined
enough clouds.  Seriously.  There are plenty in this scene, but as we
go on...
]]

The sun blazed gloriously and bathed her entire side of the shuttle in
a dazzling white light, but it would be inaccurate to say that there
was not a cloud in the sky.  A swirling tropical depression was
clearly visible over the South China Sea, extending from Guangzhou to
Kyushu, the counterclockwise swirl of its cumulus clouds clear
evidence of the ``forces'' envisioned by Coriolis.  Much of Japan's
southern archipelago was obscured by the storm system, but clear skies
over Hokkaido and Honshu left the island chain distinct and instantly
recognizable.

Andrea: _Why_are_most_of_the_great_civilizations_in_colder,_temperate_climates?_
_Japan,_England,_the_United_States,_China._
_Israel_is_hotter._  _Christianity,_Judaism,_even_Islam;_religion_comes_from_hotter_climates._

