What's going on here?  Wasn't somebody calling on the radio?

She's slacking off on the job.  Never mind that she's a superstar, a highly
trained professional on a high profile mission, on a spacewalk choreographed
to the minute, she's being paid to work, not goof off, thus, "leftists must be lazy".

I used to call it "liberals must be lazy", but she's not a liberal.
]]

Israel.  A desert land cut though by springs, wells, and one great
river that watered its fields and inundated its history.  Narrow winding streets cut through
limestone walls of an ancient city.  Beachfront condos and gleaming glass skyscrapers.  Cool resorts
on the shore of Lake Galilee.  Teenage soldiers toting Galils.
Yad Vashem.  The Occupied Territories.  Olive trees and palm fronds.

[[
I visited for a week when I was fourteen, with my parents and our Church group, led by Pastor Simmons.

I remember the hotel on Lake Galilee; they greated us with a platter of fresh fruit.  And I saw the
assult rifles, though I have no idea if they were Galils.  We went to the Garden of Gethsemane,
and the Church of the Nativity.  I don't remember Yad Vashem; I
don't think we went there.
]]

Andrea: _Who's_ever_grown_an_olive_tree_in_space?_

What would it take?  Needless to say, no living creature, not
even a tree, could survive in a vacuum, so it would have to be encased
in an aluminum satellite.  The sapling could be grown in a hydroponic
garden, but even a single full grown olive tree would never fit in the
space shuttle, or even the _Mir_ space station.  A custom satellite,
with dozens of specialized devices, would be required, along with a
constant resupply of water, carbon dioxide, and plant nutrients
without which the tree would die.  Direct sunlight, with its bizarre
45 minute day, would hopelessly upset the plant's circadian rhythm.
Unless its satellite was positioned in an geosynchronous orbit, the tree
would need to be shielded from natural sunlight and instead nurtured,
if that were the word, under artificial grow lights.  Even when full
grown, no man ever would relax from his labors under the shade of its
boughs, but would instead retrieve the olives by servicing the
satellite, likely garbed in a pressure suit, much as she was now.

Andrea looked again at her surroundings.  Any living creature that
might have stowed away aboard the Hubble had long since perished in
the harsh vacuum of space.  Astronomers had no worries of a mouse
gnarling its electrical cables, or a gnat foiling its pristine optics.
The most careful forensic examination of its surface might reveal the
RNA of a cold virus that had slipped unnoticed into the clean room
where it was assembled.  If this race of man
perished in a nuclear holocaust or a deluge from God, the satellite
would simply wait for radio instructions that would never come, or
perhaps continue to image distant galaxies and quasars according
to some pre-programmed command sequence,
oblivious to war or revolution, famine or plague,
transmitting images to a dead
planet into whose atmosphere it would one day spiral and burn.  Even
the inanimate satellite required a constant resupply of fuel from the
planet below.

_What_are_you_doing_up_here?_

Servicing the Hubble helped develop the tools and techniques needed
for men to live in space.  Plans were well underway to launch an
International Space Station, and its daunting assembly schedule made
working on the Hubble look like assembling an erector set.  After the
ISS, Mars was the next logical step...

_A_cold,_lifeless_planet_...

Andrea gazed again at the planet beneath her.  Japan was rapidly
disappearing over the western horizon, replaced by the undulating
expanse of the Pacific Ocean.  The light blue tinge of the Asian
continental shelf quickly gave way to the deep blue of the ocean
deep, unbroken except for some wispy cirrus clouds and in one spot,
the glare of reflected sunlight.

[[
See what I mean about the clouds.
]]

Yet even here, there was life.  _Even_here?_ Earth's oceans teemed
with life!  From the great leviathans hunted nearly to extinction for
their blubber and oil to the microscopic plankton they filtered
through their baleen plates, and the myriad of fish, crustaceans,
jellyfish and sea mammals in between.

_Are_you_talking_to_anyone_about_Christ?_

Well, what was the most important thing?  Wasn't it preaching the Gospel?
Isn't that what her religion taught?

_What_are_you_doing_up_here?_

[[
Oh, no, this is some kind of Christian novel, isn't it?

I'd better state some creed
to say what I believe in, so people can
argue about whether or not I'm a Christian.

I believe that the psychotic episodes I've experienced
are not, in fact, hallucinations.  I'm referring
to stuff like this, from my essay _Bicyclying_Across_America_:

    In the next minute, I had what I would describe as a mental lightening
    bolt. I suddenly saw that my problems were of my own creation - I was
    relying on myself instead of on faith. I was going to ride the bike; I
    was going to put up the tent; I had the money to buy food. I saw that
    what I needed to do was get rid of all that. The next day was Labor
    Day and everything was closed, so I rode on the Flagstaff. Here my
    bike trip ended.

    I agonized for a day or two, then committed myself. On Wednesday
    morning, crying, I took the bike for a last ride. Finding a local
    church, I gave the pastor the bike and most all the gear, telling him
    to do what he wanted with it. With my last money, I bought a pack to
    carry, and paid for postage to mail my wallet, contact lenses, and few
    other things home.

These are not hallucinations.

They're genuine spirtual revelations from God, more
precisely the Holy Spirit, which is, to me, a omniscient force
with foreknowledge of the future,
seemingly infinite wisdom, and also love.

Another amazing experience came one night in Anchorage after I
preached to a group of about two hundred men.  I had been attending
a large men's Bible study, on the Book of Revelation, for four or five months.  At each
weekly meeting, one of the leaders would give a message, but
at the final meeting, everyone was given the opportunity
to stand up and speak.  I stood up and spoke, though I
was scared to do it, not scared of any physical violence,
but scared of public speaking on a controversial topic.
I remember speculating on the possibility
that democracy could be one of the beasts in the prophecy,
because "the whole world marvels after the beast, and
nobody can defeat the beast in war."  I remember being
jeered from the audience, too, which included a former
Lieutenant Governor of Alaska, I was told.

On the drive back to the University of Alaska,
my friend the driver told me that if my message
was true it would have resonated with people,
and it didn't.

After he dropped me off at the Science and Engineering
Building, I went inside, as I usually did, and set up
my laptop to do some late work on whatever the
project of the day was.

I soon shut my laptop.  I was overcome with a
powerful sensation that I can only decribe as
"the peace of God, which passes all understanding".
I couldn't do any work.  I just packed my bag
and walked back to my homeless campsite enveloped
in this overarching sensation of peace.

How can make decisions without the guidance of this Spirit?

I'm always wondering if some little "feeling" is the
guidance of the Spirit, because I've felt it so powerful and so real,
and I'm always looking for it?

How can I decide what plane to get on without its guidance?

That's an allusion to _My_Confession_, which tells the
story of how I got on the wrong plane in Anchorage,
even though I had clear guidance from the Spirit
not to do it.

So that's the Holy Spirit.

I pray to Jesus.  I started praying to Jesus one day in
Anchorage.  I used to remember the exact date, but I forgot.
I had prayed to "Our Father, who Art in Heaven" for years,
since I was a child, but I starting thinking about
the Book of Revelation, how Jesus said
"He who conquers, I will grant him to sit with me on my throne
as I myself conquered and sat down with my Father on his throne"
and how in the Book of Mathew He said
"All authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me"

I concluded that Jesus was a pretty powerful guy with
all that authority given to Him, and there was no reason
not to pray to Him because He might not be identically God, or because said to pray to
"Our Father".  So I did.  Just walking around the
tennis courts in Delaney Park Strip, I prayed
fervently to Jesus, maybe for the first time in my life.

Over the course of the next fifteen minutes, I witnessed
the most amazing rainbow display that I have ever
seen in my life.  First one brilliant rainbow appeared
in the sky to the southeast.  Then a second
rainbox appeared within it!  Finally even
a third rainbow appeared!  I've never witnessed a
triple rainbow at any other time in my life,
and the three nested rainbows dominated the sky.

Coincidence?  Appearing within minutes of a fervent
prayer to Jesus?  It's possible, but I see a connection.

So I started praying to Jesus, and I still do!

Ahh, yes, my childhood.  You knew it was a religious
novel already because I had mentioned my trip to
the Holy Land, didn't you!?

Yes, I was raised as a Christian boy from birth,
and of course this influenced me greatly.

Many of us feel that the message of Jesus is
so important that we instill it in our children.

Yet make no mistake - I'm a Christian because I
believe in Jesus Christ.  I beleive in Him
mainly because of what I've read about Him
in the Bible.  He sounds like a pretty cool master,
and I decided to take my chances with Him years ago.

I truly hope 


Men start pursuing selfish aims, and fall away from God.




]]

"_Columbus_, Houston, for EVA."

Andrea nearly jumped in her suit.  Why had she stop working on the
ECUs?  Had he just called her already?  How long had she been just
floating here?  Pressing a button on front of her spacesuit, she keyed
the suit's radio.

% "Houston, _Columbus_ EVA, go ahead, Kyle."

Andrea: "Houston, _Columbus_, loud and clear, Kyle."

"Andrea, we'd like you to take another attempt at latching the gyro door."

The gyro door.  She had closed it after replacing the gyro assemblies,
then Goddard had attempted to latch the door remotely, but the latches
hadn't locked.  They had moved on to the electrical control units and
solar array carriers while ground controllers had studied the problem.

"We think the temperature changed enough while the door was open to
keep it from latching.  If you and Story each apply some pressure on
both ends, we'll try again to latch it."

