[[
Oh, captain, my captain.  Probably the character I identify with the most.  He's me, more than anything else.

He's a classic flawed Greek hero, while Andrea Yeats is the Ayn Rand style superman, with no major character flaws.

Is Mercuriou's fatal flaw his ego?  He's super talented, he's an overachiever, and it's gone to his head.

His rejection of classical morality is another great flaw.  He doesn't seem to be bound by
any inhibition on theft or even kidnapping.

In the classic Greek mold (aluded to by the Greek mythological character in the title), his flaw
must somehow destroy him, like Odysseus murdering his father, marrying his mother, and finally
putting his own eyes out when he learns the truth.  In our story, the flawed hero flashes through
a brilliant plan that stokes his ego and gives him worldwide fame only to see it collapse in a moment as he
attempts to push the envelope one too many times.

If there's any kind of twist to this, it's that as a suicidal wreck, instead of putting
his eyes out, he turns to God, achieves one last great impossible triumph, then dies in a blaze of glory.

Does he want fame to give him a platform for his grievances more than he wants Mars?  I think so, but
he's also swallowed his own B.S. to the point where he really thinks Mars is the solution.

Why does anyone follow him?

It's easy to say "because he stole a billion dollars", because lots
of people _will_ follow a rich man because he's rich.
Burns is an amoral technocrat who follows him because he gets to play with high-tech toys.
Alister follows him because he's young and easily duped by the speeches.
Vic never really follows him, and neither does Andrea; both are there to offer themselves as a moral anchor.

Studying anything for a solid hour a day produces results quickly.  I'd pick Spanish over Latin, though.

I wasn't rejected by the University of Chicago, but I was accepted by MIT, and choose to go to Maryland instead.
I've even got a degreee to show for that bonehead move.

Vic's appearance and mannerisms are patterned off of Vic, and I don't remember his last name,
who was another extended guest at Shiloh,
the Christian community in Sulphur Springs, Arkansas where I spent a summer.
]]

