the human race is going into space, we've got to jump start it and
show the world that ordinary people can do it, not just seven colonels
and majors in a space shuttle!  And _to_hell_ with what our
great leaders here on Earth think about it!"

Mercuriou: "Picture yourself in a spacesuit, Alister!  Picture
yourself on the first manned mission to Mars!"

Mercuriou returned to the window and gazed out again over the ocean.
The steady rain had cooled the air and precipitated a dense fog that
rose from the sea and enveloped the land.  Beyond the edge of the
cliff there was only mist; the rhythmic sound of beating surf rose
from an unseen beach a hundred feet below.

Mercuriou: "...but it all sounds so crazy... too wild to be true!"

He turned and looked Alister straight in the eye.  The young man was
plastered back in his chair, his eyes riveted on Mercuriou.

Mercuriou: "I think you're intrigued, Alister!  So check out our
launch complex, and _then_ tell me what you think!"


T - 112 days    Christians must seem crazed

Burns: "Basically what we've done is to build a shell of carbon
molecules, what is called fullerene, and fill it with metallic
hydrogen, which is a very good rocket propellant but is only stable at
high pressure.  Either the metallic hydrogen needs a lot of external
pressure to hold it together, or a small ball of metallic hydrogen is
exerting tremendous outway pressure trying to fly apart, you can look
at it in either way.  We've kept the metallic hydrogen under high
pressure by filling it into a molecule of fullerene.  In fact, we need
two molecules of fullerene, one right inside the other, to maintain
the hydrogen under pressure."

Burns: "The net result is a rocket propellant that is liquid at room
temperature and a specific impulse of 1500 seconds, which is as good
as you get from a turbofan engine.  So you can build a rocket ship
that flies like an airplane."

[[
We've been promised this line of B.S.
