[[
Why Libya?

On July 4, 1985, an epic baseball game in Atlanta ended at
4 am the next morning, at which point the stadium crew
fired off the scheduled Independence Day fireworks celebration.
According to 

https://www.parkerpioneer.net/sports/article_6f562562-9dde-11e9-b8de-c3c24e49dd81.html

the police were called asking if the city had been bombed.

I think I read somewhere that at least one person thought
the city was being attacked by Libya, but now I can't
find a reference to that.

My first reaction to reading this was to ridicule these
Americans as fools.  How could Libya possibly attack
Atlanta?  The Reagan administration had a big hyped-up
confrontation with Libya, whose government was accused
of trying to get nuclear weapons, supporting terrorism,
and claiming more than their territorial limit, so
people just fit events
into the reality projected on T.V., no matter
how absurd the conclusion.

But after 9/11 happened, I reconsidered.  Foreign states
are more capable of striking America than I had given
them credit for, and Libyian agents had already bombed both
Rome and Berlin.

Given the timeline of the novel, Iraq would make more sense.

What would people, think, really?  Seeing rocket after rocket
streaking into the sky, I think I'd assume that it was our
military launching them, and that we'd gone to war not
with Libya or Iraq, but Russia or China.
