Mercuriou: "Free technology isn't just about free software, it's about
the environment; it's about going green.  What happens when one of
your capitalist gizmos breaks?  You toss it into the nearest landfill.
Now if the design is open, that device can be repaired.  The
capitalists don't want technology that can be
repaired.  They want throw-away technology.  Instead of repairing
these devices, they want you to buy a new one.  Going green isn't
government mandated carbon scrubbers on smoke stacks.  It's building clean, open,
sustainable technology that everyone can build, improve on, and
repair, and the first step is make sure everyone knows how it is
designed and built."

Mercuriou: "We're committed to freedom of travel as a fundamental
human right.  True freedom comes not from an election, but from
variety among nations, coupled with the freedom to travel.  I call on
the United States to open her borders, to become once again the nation
that beckoned 'give me your tired, your poor, your huddled masses
yearning to be free'.  Our own borders are completely open; anyone can
come to Mars, and anyone can leave."

Mercuriou: "We will, of course, abolish this outrageous drug war on
Mars.  It is a gauntlet thrown at the foot of liberty, the
government's claim that it can tell the individual what he can put in
his own body.  All of these 'people's governments' are the same.  They
always end up at war with their own people, and most of them call it
war, too.  The Drug War is America's Cultural Revolution, our
Committee of Public Safety.  We've got a problem, The People are going
to fix it, and the government is going to make the people do it."

Mercuriou: "We're going to build a society where people respect each
other, respect each other's talents and well as each other's
differences of opinion.  We're going to preach tolerance, not Zero
Tolerance.  We're going to build a society where people like each
other, and help each other out."

Mercuriou: "Some of you are wondering how we funded our launch.  Well,
how could we have funded it?  Venture capital?  Only if I'd lied
through my teeth about my true intentions, right?  The government?
They only put Air Force colonels into space, don't they?  So we
developed, let's say, an alternative source of financing.  We robbed a
few banks."

Mercuriou: "I feel as bad about ripping off capitalists as I would
about ripping off communists or fascists, because to me they're the
same.  Just another bunch of men with some nightmare system to be
jammed down everyone's throats."

[[
It's a bit over the top, but remember, this is our uber-egotistical
Captain Mercuriou speaking, who hasn't experienced his
coming religious conversion.
]]

Mercuriou: "The only opportunity America offers is the opportunity to
sell your soul to these bastards, I mean you really convince them that
you're one of them, that you believe in their nightmare philosophy of
greed, you bring them on your management team, you sign off on some
'business plan' that tells how you're going to patent and control this
technology once it's developed, because they won't do anything for
anyone unless they're getting money for themselves, and then you fight
like hell just to keep 51 percent.  Or you toil away in your garage
for ten years of nights and weekends while working some stupid job
just to pay for the stupid garage, and I'm not much of a garage
guy."

[[
Hewlett-Packard was founded in a garage in Palo Alto,
during the Great Depression.
]]

Mercuriou: "See, spaceflight _can_ be done, but we live in a society
hell-bent on forcing people to work for a System, and telling them
constantly that they have freedom.  You don't believe me?  Ask
yourself if you'd rather be flying into space right now or doing
whatever mindless job you've got?  Our great capitalist leaders could
be mass producing spacecraft by the thousands.  Ask yourselves, 'if
they needed them for a war...'?"

Mercuriou: "Let's apply their own rationale.  I'm 'helping them
compete'.  If a few banks go out of business, so what?  Throw it into
a chapter!  It's nothing personal; businesses fail every day.  I'm
developing technology to fly to Mars, so the whole society benefits."

[[
"We'll have the company.  We'll throw it in a chapter" is a Donald Trump quote, explaining
how he has used American bankruptcy laws to his benefit.
]]

Mercuriou: "Oh, and one other thing... I'm not part of the
majority... I'm a druggie!  I'm a socialist!  I'm an anarchist!  I'm
farther left than Jane Fonda!  I'm more anti-American than Eagle Six!
I'm against everything 'The People' believe in, and they're against
everything I'm for!  I'm not part of the majority, and I don't like
democracy."

[[
Who is Eagle Six, anyway?

Presumably, in standard military parlance, the commanding officer of a unit code-named "Eagle".

I liked the name and wanted to use it at this point in the novel,
so I decided to adopt it as a pen name, changed the authorship of the novel,
and set out looking
for various ways to assume "Eagle Six" as a moniker.  I created
a new email account eaglesix@freesoft.org and used
that identity to contact a literary agent about publishing
_Icarus_Wing_.  I eventually received a rejection letter
pointed addressed to "Mr. Baccala".  Maybe I took it too far,
but I don't think so.

Is Captain Mercuriou "more anti-American than Eagle Six"?

Well, at this point in the novel, the character is rabidly anti-American,
hates America, really, for how he has been treated when he tried
to make a language learning tool freely available to the world.
The author, on the other hand, is only anti-American in a tongue-and-cheek
manner, with all of his pompous anti-Americanism (the requirements
list at the beginning of the novel) gradually
exposed as nothing more than sly innuendo.

So, yes, Captain Mercuriou _is_ more anti-American than Eagle Six!
]]

Mercuriou: "'The People'.  They make it sound like it's what _all_ the
people want.  Then why do people blow up federal buildings; why do
they bomb our embassies, why do they burn the country's flag?  Why do
we have the largest prison system in the world?  Do the people locked
up in there choose their own leaders?"

[[
Timothy McVeigh blew up the Oklahoma City Federal Building;
American embassies have been bombed in at least three cities
(Beirut, Dar es Salaam, and Nairobi) by Islamic fundamentalists,
and flag burning has been practically become a cliche.
]]

Mercuriou: "Obviously, there's a lot of people who don't agree with
America, and I'm one of them.  The majority makes up these rules, and
then expects everyone else to obey just because they're made 'through
a democratic process'.  People obey the rules because they're afraid
of what will happen to them if they don't.  The only thing that's
different about democracy is that it's a different group of people
making the rules.  In Russia it was the proletariat; in Germany it was
the Aryan race; here it's the majority.  It's always the same.  Some
big bunch of people think that because they're more genetically
advanced, or because they're the workers, or because there's more of
them than anybody else, that they become 'The People' and they have
the right to rule over everybody else."

Mercuriou: "But there are alternatives!  Not many left on Earth, mind
you.  Earth is civilized, which means it's been conquered, colonized,
and commercialized.  No matter where you go, there's some established
government, be it democracy or dictatorship, and you're just a little
cog that better turn when its supposed to and not need too much oil.
Out here, though, an entire solar system is waiting to be tamed!"

Mercuriou: "The first thing we're going to do is land on Mars, and
plant our flag there, because that is where our capital will be!  Then
we'll explore the asteroid belts.  If we find almost anything
valuable, gold or silver, platinum or pure silicon, it'll be 1849 all
over again!  And when you think that there's a whole planet out there,
all broken up into pieces already..."

Mercuriou: "Then we'll have something Earth wants!  Then we'll trade
with them on equal terms!  Then we'll have freedom!"

Mercuriou: "Think about joining us!  Maybe not literally, at least not
yet, but perhaps spiritually?  We have a website, when it is not
blocked.  We have satellite equipment, when it is not jammed.  What
skills can you offer?  Let us know!  Write a biography of yourself!
Upload it to our website!  Join our movement and help build a new
tomorrow!  Onward Martians!  Onward to Mars!"

[[
It's supposed to be a "long political rant".  I don't want it
to be so long as to bore the reader, so I tried to make
it just long enough to qualify as a "long political rant".
]]


T + 3 days    authority must be defied

_Xplorer_One_ began her third full day in orbit amid a jumble of cargo
modules, nearly two dozen of which had now been assembled into a
dense, interlocking tree.  Burns and Alister were planning their next
series of orbital maneuvers, while Vic was organizing the medical
supplies and Mercuriou reviewed video recordings of the major
political talk shows.  Andrea was squirreled away in module C-3 Electronics
Lab, studying the ship's infamous "library".

It was extensive, numbering well over ten thousand books, completely
electronic, and mostly illegal. Every major publisher of technical
books in the English language had been targeted by Burns' super-hack,
and the few books they wanted which Alister couldn't spirit off from
the publishers' computers had been purchased and scanned in by illegal
immigrants. Without launching more than a few pounds of books, most of
those for nostalgic value, the _Xplorer_One_ crew enjoyed easy access
to major reference works on every aspect of technology. There was an
entire book, for example, simply titled _Uranium_, that described
almost everything known about the chemistry of that important element
-- it's dozens of compounds, their properties, the reactions used to
convert between them, and of course its nuclear properties, despite
the fact that the ship carried only a small sample of uranium in its
chemistry lab and Burns had no intention at all of using nuclear
fuel. In fact, all of the major chemical elements were well
represented, with entire books on silicon, iron, and dozens on carbon
and its various compounds. The ship's custom navigation software was
littered with references that hyperlinked directly into a book called
_Celestial_Mechanics_. There were dictionaries, encyclopedias,
handbooks, and entire scientific journals. There were books on antenna
theory, orbital mechanics, geology, hydroponics, plant pathology, and
Mercuriou's hand-picked collection of literature, both in translation
and in the original tongues.

Almost as impressive was the software collection. Every major
technical product was present, many including all of their source code,
stolen from the manufacturer's computers by Burns and Alister. The
scientific software was second to none. In addition to Gaussian and
programs like it, there were sophisticated packages to model and
simulate high-frequency microwave circuitry, the most advanced robotic
control software from Japan, factory blueprints for a complete
semiconductor fabrication plant, and several sophisticated
mathematical packages.  There were even plans for a W-88 thermonuclear warhead!
The three-pound computer tablet in Andrea's
hand offered the same information that would fill an elite university
library, and the same software packages available at the most
prestigious research centers. The legal penalties for acquiring and
possessing all of it added up to more than a hundred and eighty years
of prison time.

[[
Can't be done, you say?

Sounds a bit like what China is stealing from the United
States right now (the "greatest transfer of wealth in history", according
to Keith Alexander, a former NSA director), so I tossed in
the nuclear warhead because, yes, they've stolen that too.

https://www.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/resources/1999/cox.report/theft/pg1.html

I confess that I assign my characters the capabilities of nation-states,
but isn't the same suspension of disbelief required to swallow something like
_Moonraker_'s secret shuttle launch facility (for six simultaneous launches, no less!)
in the Amazon rainforest?

Both stories ask us to believe, "because he's
filthy rich", and most people buy that!
]]

Alister: "We've got a pressure drop," Alister announced on the flight
deck, as a chime sounded and an amber alert window appeared on the LCD
screen to his right.  Burns stopped programming the flight computer
and Mercuriou floated in from his captain's quarters.

Alister: "We're down to 97.4 kilopascals," Alister informed them,
reading off the atmospheric pressure.

Mercuriou: "That's not much," Mercuriou observed.

Burns_black: "Yeah, but it should be a closed system," Burns answered,
sporting a new T-shirt that asked "Why drink and drive, when you can
fry and fly?"

Alister: "97.3," Alister stated.

Burns: "Let's go to Condition Zed," Burns suggested, and Mercuriou nodded.

Mercuriou: "Captain to crew, set Condition Zed," Mercuriou announced
into the microphone clipped to his shirt, while Alister keyed a
command sequence on his computer.  An audible chime sounded throughout
the ship, and the hydraulic doors separating the different modules
hissed shut.

[[
Condition Zebra or Zed, apparently, is a standard "material condition"
in the U.S. Navy, and indicates a "battle closure condition" of water-tight doors:

https://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/USN/Wallin/Wallin-9.html
]]

Andrea: "What's happening?" Andrea asked as she watched the door close
on C-3.

Mercuriou: "We're closing the airtight doors, Dr. Yeats, we seem to
have a pressure leak.  Vic, where are you?"

Vic: "I'm in sickbay, of course," the doctor answered, stopping his
inventory of the ship's drug supply.

Mercuriou: "He's got a spacesuit in there if he needs it.  What about
Dr. Yeats?"

Burns was shaking his head, no.

Andrea: "I don't think there's a suit in here.  All I see is
oscilloscopes and signal generators."

Alister: "We're down to 90 in C-4.  Looks like the rest are holding."

Mercuriou: "That's right next to where Yeats is."

Burns: "It's probably a micro meteor strike, 'cause we're not fully
assembled yet and the shield isn't in place.  But if we lose 'C' node,
she'll be cut off, so we probably want to get her out of there."

Mercuriou: "OK, Dr. Yeats, why don't you exit the module you're in and
come back here to where we've at least got a spacesuit for you, then
we'll check on the problem, it looks like it's in C-4."

Burns: "I can open the pressure doors from here."

Burns opened the door to C-3, and Andrea pulled herself through it
into a mating node.  Burns next opened the door to C-core, which lead
back towards the 767.

But Andrea didn't go there. Instead, she went to the door leading into
C-4, and was about to ask what its pressure was, when she saw it
displayed on the LCD panel by the door. 87 kilopascals. She knew as a
rough rule of thumb that supplemental oxygen wasn't needed until the
pressure dropped to 70. She keyed the sequence on the panel that
opened the door. Designed to seal its pressurized contents against an
exterior vacuum, it popped open under the force of the higher pressure
outside, accompanied by a whoosh of air flowing into the damaged
node. Andrea's sinuses popped under the pressure change.

Andrea: "I'm going to take a look at the problem in here," Andrea
informed the others as she pushed herself into the node.

On the flight deck, colors changed on the computer animation of the
ship's layout.

Alister: "She just opened the door to C-4!" Alister declared in surprise.

Mercuriou: "That node appears to be damaged, it's loosing pressure, Doctor!"

In C-4, Andrea could hear a quiet whooshing of air.  She removed her
water bottle from her belt and carefully squeezed it to release a
stream of liquid aimed straight down the center of the module, then
watched to see where it went.

Meanwhile, Mercuriou had dove to the rear of the 767 and grabbed a spacesuit.

Mercuriou: "Open the door!"

Burns: "Opening main airlock," Burns stated in a resigned tone of
voice as he keyed a computer panel. Mercuriou dove into A-core with
the suit.

Vic: "What's going on?"

Mercuriou flushed red, clenched his teeth, and smacked his fist into his palm.

Mercuriou: "We've got a pressure leak, Vic, and Dr. Yeats, as usual,
is EXACTLY where we don't want her to be!"

Alister: "Aren't you going to prep?"

Mercuriou: "I don't have time! What if she gets stuck in there?"

Andrea released the harnesses on several large packing crates and
moved them aside to follow the trail of the water droplets. A wave of
fear swept over her. _You_have_no_spacesuit_. Calming herself, she
said a silent prayer, _Father,_watch_out_for_me_in_here._

Andrea: "Alister, keep reading the pressure off to me."

Alister: "It's at 82 now. It came back up for a second when you opened
the door, but now it's dropping again."

Burns: "Opening 'B' node," Burns dryly noted as he continued to open
pressure doors in front of the captain, now moving down the central
chain of cargo modules, bumping against walls as he went, partly
because he hadn't fully learned how to maneuver in zero-gee, but also
because he grew ever more irate the further he went.

Meanwhile, Andrea had found the pinhole leak at the root of the
problem. Unlike the space shuttle, designed for manned spaceflight
operations from the beginning, the cargo modules were large pressure
tanks with cargo containers secured to their side. At times this meant
an inconvenient jumble of conduit that could have been better
designed, but in this case it meant easy access to the punctured wall
of the module. She began looking around for something to plug the hole
with, just as Mercuriou opened the door and propelled himself into the
module.

Mercuriou: "Doctor Yeats, we've got to get a few things clear right now..."

Andrea: "Excuse me... sir," she interrupted as she reached for the
spacesuit and pulled out one of its gloves. Turning back to the
puncture, she slapped the glove against it.

Andrea: "That'll hold until we can patch it permanently," she
announced, then put her left hand on her hip while still holding a
cargo strip with her right.

Andrea: "You wanted to get some things clear? First, no matter how
much reserve oxygen you've got now, it's not enough. Second, it's a
lot easier to find the leak while there's still air in here.  Finally,
bring two suits next time.  It'd really suck if we both got stuck in
here with only one suit between us."

Red-faced, Mercuriou stared at her for several seconds, then turned
and left without without saying another word.

[[
I have no idea how professional astronauts would view this scene.
Is she foolish?  Brave?  I don't know.  In the novel, she's
knowledgeable and brave.
]]


T + 5 days    America must be run by fools

[[
The three fools symbolize, advocate for, and represent three foolish philosophies
that dominate American political life: conservative capitalism, liberalism, and the religious right.

The goal of this chapter is to show up everything wrong with capitalism except the Christian case against it,
because Mercuriou hasn't had his religion conversion yet.

Capitalism discriminates against people who are generous.

Some might argue that this chapter, and the others like it, is too preachy,
but I disagree.  Dialog has been used effectively in books like
_Two_New_Sciences_.  Shakespeare wrote almost nothing but dialog.

Where dialog goes off the rails in _Men_Like_Gods_, for example, it gets preachy,
and that was H. G. Wells, so even the best writers fall victim
to this enticing temptation.

_Men_Like_Gods_ doesn't work because there's only one voice speaking.
There's two characters, but because they agree so much, they sound like
my sterotypical progressives in the next chapter.  All they do
is agree with each other.

Effective dialog has to present believable antagonists.  I try to
make mine a little bit goofy to help undermine their arguments, though.
]]

Perhaps because of his attitude, perhaps because of his altitude,
perhaps because of his impunity, completely beyond the reach of any
terrestrial authority, or perhaps simply because of what he said and
how he said it, _Captain_ Marc Mercuriou seemed to incite the ire of
nearly every American political leader, regardless of party
affiliation or personal background.

Ecks: "Get the hell out of the left lane, fifty-five!"

[[
The most common American speed limit is 55, and the left
lane is customarily reserved for faster traffic.  The
politician is not only breaking the law by speeding,
but is actually angry at someone else for obeying the law,
who he denigrates as a "fifty-five"

He's also in a big rush.

Of course, I'd also be angry at somebody driving 55 in the left lane.
]]

Congressman Richard Ecks yelled out his window, leaned on his horn and zoomed around the
slower car, passing it on the right.  His radio and TV show had been
on the air longer than he had been in Congress, and this harried
commute from his office on Capital Hill to his studio in Fairfax had
become a daily ritual.  He pulled into his reserved parking spot and
hustled inside, skipping the elevator and instead jogging up three
flights of stairs.

[[
A parody of Rush Limbaugh, may he rest in peace.

Ecks symbolizes capitalism.

Certainly by 2005 or so I had conceived of calling these
characters X, Y, and Z, or Ecks, Wye, and Zee.
]]

Ecks: "What did I miss?" he gasped as he reached the top, where his
producer met him with a blank stare.

"Nothing.  We're still on with the space captain at five."

Ecks gulped down one of the steamed broccoli and banana seed
milkshakes that he relied on to keep his 300 pound bulk under control.
He changed, put on his makeup, drank half of another milkshake at his
desk on the set, then set it out of view as the cameras came on.

[[
Rush Limbaugh pushed various weight loss schemes:

https://abcnews.go.com/GMA/story?id=8234457

My best friend loves steamed broccoli, but can you imagine such a thing?
How would you extract the banana
seeds, anyway?  Somebody will figure it out.  Remember, it's parody, he has
to look like a "fool".
]]

Ecks: "Good evening, and welcome to 'Outside the Beltway'."

[[
"His radio and TV show had been on the air longer than he
had been in Congress", and it's always been called
"Outside the Beltway".

The Beltway is the Washington, DC beltway.

He imagines himself a political outsider, pushing
populist views against the capitol's liberal elite.
After he gets elected to Congress, he still fancies
himself a populist outsider, but it becomes harder to
maintain this image, thus his frantic commute.  He
still refuses to admit that so many of those liberal
policies he despises were promoted by elected Congressmen,
just like him, and that he has become a Washington, D.C.
wheeler-and-dealer, just like them.
]]

Ecks: "Capitalism has produced a society with the highest standard of
living that has ever been seen on this planet.  People are well-fed,
well-housed, generally content with their jobs, with a surplus of
leisure time and disposable income.  Yet our opponents slam us at
every turn because they can't stand the idea of people working hard
and getting rewarded for that work.  Now this thief comes along, this
criminal who has taken advantage of our society, stolen from our
businesses and our government, lied, cheated; he comes along with the
nerve to blame capitalism for what?  For letting him take advantage of
our freedom?  For giving him the opportunity to pull of one of the
greatest con jobs in history -- the 'Republic of Mars'?  Let me start
by asking you, _Captain_ -- how do you justify your theft?"

Mercuriou: "Same way they justified Hiroshima -- it had to be done."

Ecks: "Hiroshima?  We were at war, a war Japan started!"

Mercuriou: "_Japan_?!  What _Japan_?  The women and children, the
innocent civilians that died, _they_ started the war?  _They_ attacked
us?  We did what we _had_ to do to win, and there was some 'collateral
damage'.  Same thing here.  Nobody even got killed!"

[[
Various American leaders have justified not only
Hiroshima, but also slavery, the armed conquest of the American native tribes,
the armed conquest of Mexico, and a slew of lesser conquests
designed to contain either Communism or Islamic fundamentalism.

Of course, Japan justified the Rape of Nanjing, the conquest of China,
the torture of American prisoners, and the sneak attack on Pearl Harbor.

Just saying.
]]

Ecks: "And how... what war... again, how do you justify your theft?"

Mercuriou: "It had to be done!  To stop capitalism!  To stop democracy!
It had to be done!"

Ecks: "...and all that justifies theft how?"

Mercuriou: "It has to be stopped!  Just like fascism!  Just like
communism!  Now, I did what I had to do.  I've answered your question,
so move on."

[[
I imagine that he really believe this.  His egomania, to me, is not
demonstrated so much by his theft, but by the fact that he really
thinks that his plan will set in motion the defeat of capitalism!
]]

There was a pause, and then another.

Ecks_Mercuriou_Ecks: "...and this 'Republic of Mars'... how is its government structured?"  \hfil\break\-\quad\hskip 1in "I'm the acting chief executive"  \hfil\break\-\hskip 2in "of course"

Ecks_Mercuriou: "...should we call you President?"
\hfil\break\-\quad\hskip 1in "Captain"

A cocky smirk spread over Marc
Mercuriou's face, and he reached dramatically for a prominently positioned red switch.

[[
The implicit threat is to end the interview, but he's the big star now,
so nobody is inclined to challenge him.
]]

Ecks: "Alright, _Captain_, capitalism may not be perfect, and this
country may not be perfect, but what sets us apart from communism and
fascism is our commitment to freedom."

Mercuriou: "Freedom?  What freedom?  You have the freedom to be a
capitalist, or to work for the capitalists, or to be put homeless on
the streets!"

Ecks: "Well, I guess freedom _is_ limited for people who don't want to
work..."

Mercuriou: "Let's shortcut this debate.  'Work' is a propaganda term
that means 'making money', right?"

[[
"Work" _is_ a propaganda term.  I define a "propaganda term" as a term
with multiple definitions or connotations that is used in a deliberately
vague way in order to obtain victory in an argument or debate.

"Work" can mean "making money", or "taking care of yourself",
or "doing something productive", and they all get mixed up
together to the benefit of the propagandist.

Other important propaganda terms are "freedom" and "democracy".

Freedom - are we talking specifics, or the freedom to do whatever
you want?  Can I commit murder?  Is that freedom?

Democracy - OK if I pile a hundred thousand people into your
state for election day?  Is that still "democracy"?
]]

Ecks: "No, 'work' means 'work'!  Work is what you do to put food on
the table.  We have to work in order to eat, Captain.  We have to work
to have houses, cars, clothes, computers, all of it.  We have to
sustain ourselves!"

Mercuriou: "How do you sustain yourself?  By refusing to do for people
unless they pay you?  How does that sustain anyone?  But you dodged my
question, Congressman.  Are you defining work as making money, or
doing something productive?"

Ecks: "There's no difference!  That's the beauty of capitalism; people
get rewarded for hard work, and have the freedom to invest however
they please!"

Mercuriou: "No difference!  Some kid makes millions throwing a
baseball, and a father of five make pennies pushing a hot dog cart!"

Ecks: "We have _freedom_!  People can choose
what work to do, and what to do with their money.  You can be a
businessman if you choose, you can be a social worker if you choose,
you can be an author, you can be a doctor, you can be a baseball
player; it's nothing imposed by the government; it's your choice!  You
can be Mother Teresa!  And you don't like to hear this, Captain, but
most people want to better themselves through hard work, not
charity handouts!"

Mercuriou: "Capitalism rewards people who _do_for_themselves_!  If you
won't work for them, you're thrown away like a piece of human garbage,
you're talked to like garbage, you're treated like garbage, you're
told to _get_a_job_ and _do_what_you're_told_!  The only way to get
rewarded for hard work is to slap a credit card form on everything!"

Ecks: "Because in the real world, if you just give everything away,
you'll be out of business!"

[[
The American people, with their "freedom", could have
choosen to live lives of sacrifice to help the world; instead most people
seem to want the biggest pile of money they can get.  The United States
could be known as a nation that is gives its technology
away for free, has turned the Library of Congress into
an Internet Library of Alexandria, always welcomes
immigrants, and encourages smaller nations to become
self-sufficient, but instead it's become known as
the land of big business.

To be sure, some Americans have choosen that life of sacrifice,
but the majority have chosen something much different,
and nobody should kid themselves into thinking
that democracy won't be judged by what it
has produced.
]]

Mercuriou: "That's right!  That's the 'freedom' of capitalism -- you
become a capitalist or you'll be put out of business!  We pay pitchers
millions a year, support video game, music and film industries that
rake in billions a year, blow half a trillion a year on the military,
but we can't afford to house people?  Capitalism is
depraved!  Your leaders are trash!  Your entire society is built on
forced labor for these creeps!"

[[
In the first edition, I had "feed people in restaurants" instead
"house people", and I changed it because this country's churches
do a halfway decent job of feeding people.  Housing the poor
they don't, and it's a serious problem because people are
crippled when they lack what architects call "pride of place",
or, in other words, a "home".
]]

Ecks: "Freedom, Captain, Freedom!!  Who the hell are you to tell
someone else what they can and can't do with their property?!!  How
dare you, you socialist crook, you shameless thief, how dare you tell
someone who's sweated tears and blood that they have to give
everything away for free?!  I've let you rant on because I felt like
listening to your bombast! You're like a blind man screaming 'You
Blinked!'  How are you so much better than all these terrible
capitalists?  You're the worst kind of capitalist -- you've stolen
billions of dollars to build your own dream!  You needed
money -- that's why most people go to work in the morning!  That's why
all these evil capitalists don't just publish all their books on the
Internet -- because the authors need money to write them, money to
print them, money to put food on the table in front of their children!
You've got a problem with _authority_, _Captain_!  Let's take a break
now and I'll introduce our next guest when we return."

[[
Congressman Ecks can't just be a straw man or the dialog wouldn't
be very captivating.  Later, I'll try to make sure our
reformed Captain Mercuriou does a better job of answering him.
For now, let me just say that all of his cynical talking points are
absolutely true.  One of the few rational reasons not to
live as he suggests is if you believe in a life after death,
and that life is more important to you than this one.
]]

Senator Patricia Wye had been a fixture on the Washington scene for
decades, first as a dutiful wife and more recently as a power broker
in her own right.  Seated comfortably by the fireplace in the Senate
Reading Room, she looked about her as a pre-recorded Ecks hawked the weight loss benefits
of a banana seed diet,
The chair was positioned precisely; the coffee cup was filled to exactly
the correct level; an edge of the ornate rug could just be seen on the
video monitor.  
She waited until the tally light came on before
smiling, to make this act seem more spontaneous.  As she fell easily
into a familiar patter with Ecks, the cameraman noted that her frosted
blond coiffure hadn't changed in twenty years.

[[
A parody of Hilary Clinton, here speaking for liberalism.

EVERYTHING WRONG WITH DEMOCRACY.  CAPITALISM IS REGULATED.  GOVERNMENT
IS RUN BY ITS PEOPLE.

The Senate Reading Room in the Library of Congress
is said to be ornate, and is exclusively for the use of U.S.
Senators and their staff.
]]

Ecks: "Senator, what do you say to Captain Mercuriou?"

Wye: "Only that this country is run by its people, through their
elected representatives, and the capitalists do not own everything.
If anything, it's the other way around.  Capitalism is chosen by the
people and regulated by the government."

Mercuriou: "Oh, it's regulated, all right.  You've got laws to
regulate factories, you've got laws to regulate fisheries, you've got
laws to regulate farmers.  If you chose decent leaders to begin with,
you wouldn't need all those laws!"

Wye: "Well, we have to have laws, Captain.  Our opponents wants a
society with no rules, but my vision of capitalism is that of a level
playing field where businesses can compete honestly, officiated by the
government, much like a sporting content."

[[
"Our opponents" are the conservatives like Congressman Ecks, who
she jabs at by suggesting that they want "a society with no rules".
She's not debating Ecks directly, but she certainly doesn't agree
with him.
]]

Mercuriou: "Why?  I'll tell you why.  Because otherwise you'll have
two factory owners build on the same river.  One will be clean and
safe; the other one will just dump his waste into the nearest pond.
The first one will go out of business in a year, and the second one
will retire at forty laughing 'Ha ha ha, you can't _com-pe-te_!'"

Wye: "And we don't allow that, captain!  We allow free markets and
free enterprise because they are beneficial to society, but we also
need laws to protect the environment and ensure a level playing field,
so that good corporate citizens are not victimized by abusers.  Would
you have us abandon the Clean Air Act, or the Clear Water Act?  We
have food stamps because we're not willing to let people starve!  We
have social security and Medicare because we're not willing to put the
elderly out on the streets!"

Mercuriou: "And who pays for it all?  More taxes?  Or just run it all
up on the national credit card?  How about a magician pulling a
kerchief out of his fist -- can he do it for the Federal Reserve?"

Wye: "We have to control spending, but we're not doing it by getting
rid of the programs that we have decided are necessary."

Mercuriou: "Bottom line -- if America is so great and so wonderful,
why do we need all these government programs?"

Wye: "Because these government programs help make our society great!
We allow free enterprise, we allow competition, we allow people to
earn a reward from their labor, but we also have programs in place to
achieve a clean environment, a safe food supply, reliable
transportation, a minimal social support system.  Women and minorities
need protection against discriminatory labor practices, and children
deserve a quality education.  These decisions are made through a
cooperative political process."

Mercuriou: "Your decisions are made on a TV game show, vastly
elaborate, with stages all over the country, and oh so expensive!
You've got to be flying everywhere, giving speeches, buses, banners,
balloons, all kinds of buttons and bumper stickers!  It costs huuuuge
amounts of money to play, the judges watch everything on TV, and they
have an average IQ of 100!  This is what your government has been
since the invention of television!  It's got troops all over God's
creation, enough national debt to last a half century, the biggest
prison state in the world, a wall across its southern border, and now
it's out to enslave the planet under globalization!  I call it a Game
Show Government, and it's a disaster of truly Biblical proportions!"

Wye: "We're governed by our Constitution..."

Mercuriou: "You're governed by a TV Game Show!"

Wye firmly grabbed her head, re-adjusted her hair, then laughed.

[[
Foreshadowing her later "wardrobe malfunction".
]]

Wye: "So now you're against democracy..."

Mercuriou: "Greek gods, am I against it!?  It's tyrannical!  It's
premise, that this one group of people, this majority, are somehow
entitled to rule over everyone else just because there's more of
them; it's a tyranny!"

[[
"Greek gods" is, I believe, an original expletive that I invented
for Captain Mercuriou, meant in the sense of "My God", or "Good grief".

Now, people will read this and say that I "hate democracy" or that
I "hate the United States".

I try to recognize that the rest of the world doesn't look
any better than the United States, so whenever I'm tempted
to say that I "hate the way I've been treated in the United
States", or "hate the way the majority of the American people
have treated me", I try to rephrase this and say that
I "hate the way I've been treated in this world",
or I "hate the way the majority of people have treated me".

Furthermore, as a matter of principle, I try not to hate anything or anyone.
So I don't "hate democracy", I just don't believe in it anymore.

It can't deliver on its promises.  It can't give us this "freedom" that it hypes,
because human nature is too wicked.  What democracy has given us is a coercive society
based on forced labor for money, and that's pretty much the best you
can expect from human civilization right now.

We Christians call this "The Gospel", or the "Good News", and it doesn't sound like
good news at first, but it's the truth, and only bad news would start with a lie.
The really Good News is that there's life after death, and from the sounds of it,
it's fair, much to the dismay of people who tell us that "life isn't fair".

So don't believe the majority's hype.  Putting the masses of people in charge
produces a tyranny of people motivated by greed.

...

The only utopian communities that have survived for any
period of the time are the Catholic religious communities -
the Benedictines, the Franciscans, the Cistercians, etc,
all of whom date to medieval times.  The Mormans
are an interesting case, really about the only surviving, purely American
utopian experiment that I'm aware of,
and they've largely abandoned their utopian roots
and settled down as another Christian denomination.
]]

Wye: "We have a participatory government, Captain!  The people can
petition their government to change the laws, and if enough people
want change, the laws _will_ change!"

Mercuriou: "You didn't say the people could _participate_!  You said
the people could _choose_their_own_leaders_, but in fact only the
majority get to _choose_their_own_leaders_; they do it on a TV Game
Show; everyone else participates, and loses!  Hell, I'll take
'participatory government' any day!  You participate, and I'll make
all the decisions!  I'll even have my own TV Game Show!  What do you
say?"

[[
I'd like to have a TV Game Show.

I could even live stream it on my website!
]]

Wye: "What do the people of this country want?"

Mercuriou:  "I don't care what they want, it's not what I want!"

Wye: "What about the _majority_?"

Mercuriou: "All they want to do is to get rich, get tough, and get laid!"

[[
It's supposed to be a clever way of saying
that the majority want to make a lot of money (get rich),
they want a strong police and military (get tough),
and they want to have sex (get laid).
]]

Wye: "What about the people?"

Mercuriou: "Oh, get off your cracked track!  What's so sacrosanct
about that magic 50 percent, that _majority_?"

[[
Phonograph records are organized in tracks, and
a crack in the record will sometimes cause the needle
to skip backwards in the recording, which then repeats in a loop.
]]

Wye: "You'll have a dictatorship, captain, but I suppose that's what
you had in mind all along!"

Mercuriou: "Nobody can just rule over everyone else like that.
Nobody!  Nobody has that right!"

Wye: "I've got a mission update for you, captain!  The people of this
planet have decided on democracy and we're not going back!"

[[
One my favorite original expressions in the novel.  If you don't
agree with someone, tell them you've got a "mission update" for them!
]]

Mercuriou: "I don't care.  I won't accept it.  Nobody should."

Ecks' final guest on the program was the Reverend Caiaphas Zee, a
prominent Southern Baptist minister who had transformed a failed
presidential bid into a mega church empire, and who now seemed content to
advise the politicians he could not supplant.  Standing in his pulpit
on live T.V., clad in a black cassock and a starched white collar, a
simple wooden cross hanging from a cord around his neck, his graying
countenance seemed the very personification of a prophet of God.

[[
He's a mix of Pat Buchanan and Jerry Falwell.  Caiaphas was
the high priest who presided over the trial and execution
of Jesus.  Our Caiaphas has high priest fever - real self-righteous,
thinks he's got the Bible all figured out, always looks
to judge and condemn others.

The simple wooden cross _I_ sometimes wear postdates his considerably.

His was checked into git on June 4, 2011 via commit cffa8a,
when I working on the novel while homeless in Haleiwa, Hawaii.
That was the last date I committed anything until March 12, 2012,
and I have a commit on July 3, 2012 with comment "Bring up to date with published version".
Adding his "simple wooden cross" must have been one of the last
changes I made before ordering 100 copies of the first edition,
though the June 4th date seems strange to me, since I waited for two months
or so for those books to be delivered to Hawaii,
but surely I was in Alaska in the summer of 2011.

My cross came in the spring of 2017;
I was hitchhiking home through western Pennsylvania when
one of my drivers gifted it to me after a short ride.
The rope has broken and been replaced, but it's still
the same cross.
]]

Zee: "Captain, you are a liar and a thief!"

Mercuriou: "I've said everything I intend to say on that issue."

Zee: "Then let me say more!  We have laws not because they are made by
man, but because they are commanded by God!  We are told 'thou shall
not steal'!"

Mercuriou: "If that's all you want to discuss..."

Mercuriou reached again for the switch, but Zee thundered on.

Zee: "Throw the switch, Captain, go ahead!  That's all I want to
discuss!  'Thou Shall Not Steal'!  'Thou Shall Not Steal'!"

Mercuriou paused, then threw the switch.  Nothing happened.  He grinned.

Mercuriou: "OK, Reverend, so maybe I won't switch you off just yet."

Zee: "Thou Shall Not Steal, Captain, _Thou_Shall_Not_Steal_!  God's
laws _command_ capitalism!"

Mercuriou: "God's laws or man's laws?"

Zee: "God's laws, Captain, God's laws!  No sex!  No drugs!
And one more... _Thou_Shall_Not_Steal_!"

Mercuriou: "No sex?"

Zee: "Don't you play word games with me, mister!  You know what I
mean!  Marriage between a man and a woman!"

[[
Zee, of course, opposes adultery, homosexuality, pre-marital sex,
gender changing, polygamy, and group sex.  He himself is happily
married to his lovely wife of yadda-yadda many years.

In short, he has sex mostly the way he wants, and tells
others their sexual activities and even attractions are immoral.

Personally, I think the Gospel teaches celibacy and,
at least for some, castration (Matthew 19:12).
Giving up sex is like giving up meat or giving
up worldly possessions.  It's a sacrifice
whose purpose is to live more holy lives.
]]

Mercuriou: "Yet capitalism is moral... _why_?"

Zee: "Because God does not allow the government to steal!  The
government is responsible for public safety; the church is to handle
charity!"

Mercuriou: "After taking out a nice income for its preachers..."

Zee: "Our ministers deserve every cent of that tithe, mister!
We live that gospel every day!  Our people work to help
the poor, and many of them give quite a bit more than ten percent.  We
have some _very_ generous members in our congregation."

[[
The traditional Jewish tithe was ten percent of income to support the priesthood.
Various Christian denominations have adopted it in one form or another.
]]

Mercuriou: "You've got this nightmare of capitalism that's another
slavery all over again..."

Zee: "It is not!  We don't bind men in chains to force them to work!
You should have been a politician; instead you became a thief!  Now
nobody will listen to you!  Now I'm throwing the switch!"

Ecks interrupted before Mercuriou could fire back.

[[
Zee "throws the switch" by prevented Mercuriou from replying.
]]

Ecks: "Well, our time is growing short, captain, and it looks like our
prison system is going to remain a little short, too.  I don't think
it's worth the trouble and expense to apprehend you right now."

Mercuriou now broke out into a long, almost genuine laugh.  Ecks paused
for a moment, then kept talking without waiting for him to stop.

Ecks: "There's really no harm in leaving you be.  You'll eventually
have to come back down.  In the meantime, when you make it Mars, _if_
you make it to Mars, do us a favor.  Have the dignity to plant an
American flag there.  It's the least you can do for the country that
footed the bill."

[[
Foreshadowing - he intends to plant an American flag there, upside down in the dirt
]]


T + 7 days    it must be offensive

Mercuriou's next T.V. appearance was on a daily political talk
show, funded by the U.S. federal government, whose host had become a multi-millionaire
from book deals, speaking fees, and shrewd business dealings.

Lucy: "Good evening.  Wecome to _People_Power_, _The_People_Power_Project_,
the _Power_To_The_People_ Report, and _Populism_Now_; I'm Lucy Liberal.
Our next guest is well known to our viewers,
Dr. Alishah Reynolds-Meyers, ARM, welcome."

[[
Basically, it's Amy Goodman and Nikole Hannah-Jones, at least in this chapter.  Of course,
her "acronym" ARM is a slight variant on Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez, AOC.  Later,
ARM is fashioned more after Richard Dawkins than any American politico.

They're a send up of progressives.
They always agree with each other, and all they talk about is race.

Yes, she is actually called "ARM" conversationally.  Remember, this is satire;
all of these characters are supposed to look a little bit goofy, except
those espousing _my_ viewpoints, who look reasonable, principled, and even heoric.
]]

Dr. Alishah Reynolds-Meyers, more commonly known as ARM,
was a prominent Black activist with a prestigious tenured chair
at an Ivy League university.  Her preferred pronouns were
she/her and she sported an afro
the size of a basketball dyed black on one side
and white on the other.

[[
If you asked her, she'd say that her hair represent the ying and the yang.

Actually, a basketball is about the right size for an afro, I think.
The basketball might even be a bit too small, but it sounds good
in the novel.
]]

Lucy: "Several commentators have noticed the lack of racial diversity in the
makeup of the _Xplorer_One_ crew, ARM, all of these people are whites,
is that correct?"

ARM: "That's right, Lucy, one of them is from South Africa, which gives
this crew a _semblence_ of diversity, but of course,
Alister Compton is a _white_ South African, and we all remember the
history of White South Africa."

[[
Why is Alister from South Africa?

Becuase I knew a kid from South Africa named Alister and I liked him.
]]

Lucy Liberal now made a point of turning some pages in a file folder laid open
upon her anchor desk.  Her viewers imagined that the file folders, a prominent prop on her show, contained
every obscure fact and tantalizing tidbit bit of innuendo that could be thrown at her opponents.

Lucy: "So this crew is not racially diverse, but of course this is not
a typical American corporation or government venture, this is a criminal enterprise, right?"

ARM: "That's right, Lucy.  It just goes to show how pervasively
racist the United States of America is, that even her criminal
enterprises are pervaded by racism..."

Mercuriou: "Now, just a minute here..."

Lucy: "We're also joined by the leader of the _Xplorer_One_ mission,
Captain Marchelius Mercuriou, but I want to circle back to what ARM just said,
even America's _criminals_ are racist?!"

ARM: "Of course America's criminals are racist!  The entire society
was born and bathed in racism!  Every aspect of American culture
is pervaded by racism.  While black criminals are carjacking Jaguars
white criminals are launching private space missions!"

[[
The real Kyle's Jag briefly flashes here again.
]]

Mercuriou: "Now, just a cotton-pickin' minute here!"

Lucy: "Captain Mercuriou, please do not use that kind of racially
insensitive language on this program!"

ARM: "My ancestors were chained to plows to pick that crop you
just named... I won't even speak its name..."

[[
It's all true.  Slavery was America's gulag.

Just to be clear, the targets of the satire are progressives, not Blacks.
]]

Mercuriou: "Look, I'm just trying to say that I didn't hold a hiring fair for this mission!"

ARM: "Yet somehow you have an all white crew!"

Lucy: "Captain, we know you didn't hold a hiring fair, so how exactly was your crew selected?"

Mercuriou was becoming visibly exasperated.  He took a deep breath,
exhaled, and launched into an explaination of how his crew had been selected.

Mercuriou: "I approached two of my best friends, men I've known and trusted for years,
and asked them to embark on a venture where secrecy was paramount and trust was implicit."

ARM: "So, you asked your white crew if they wanted to steal a billion dollars and blast into space with you?"

[[
Yeah, pretty much.

Double entendre on "crew"
]]

"No, one of them is a medical doctor, and the other is a very accomplished engineer.
Along the way we encountered a very promising young chemist and software developer,
a real science and technology expert really, and persuaded him to join us.
Then Dr. Yeats joined us."

Lucy: "...and how exactly did that happen!"

Mercuriou paused again before answering.

"Dr. Yeats is a NASA engineer and astronaut who was asked to investigate
the manufacturing plant we were using as our cover.  When she discovered
the true nature of our operation, I ordered her arrested _for_a_brief_period_ to protect
the operational secrecy of the mission.  After I released her from custody, she
choose _voluntarily_ to join our crew."

[[
This is called "spin".
]]

ARM: "A _white_ astronaut!  Didn't NASA have any colored or Hispanic astronauts available!?"

Lucy Liberal flipped her pages.

Lucy: "73 percent of NASA astronauts are white."

ARM: "It's one of the least diverse populations in our country."

[[
FIGURE THIS PERCENTAGE OUT IF I HAVE TO COUNT THEM UP MYSELF

The timeframe is several months prior to 9/11.  Let's say early 2001.

Mercury - 7/7
The Next Nine - 9/9
