[[
I just had a Dr. Seuss / Theatre of the Absurd moment and
started giggling all over myself, thinking how funny it would
be to list out this enormous feast consisting of every
favorite meal I can think of.

I actually took it from a list called "Things of Men" that
I wrote during a long fast in the Chugach Mountains.

Think this better be in iambic pentameter, or people will hate
to read it because it won't scan.  Well, it better be some
kind of unrhymed verse.  Iambic pentameter is the easiest.

I used to have a computer program that looked words up
in a dictionary and marked their accents automatically,
but I marked this text by hand rather than fool around
with finding the program and getting it running.  Slashes and dashes are accented
and unaccented syllables within a word; backtick
are secondary accents; dots are
single syllable words that can't be categorized
as either accented or unaccented except by actually
scanning the line of text.  I like to read it
a little more heavily accented on the iambic pattern
just to make sure it scans well; like a spellcheck.
It's meant to be read normally, though, as prose,
so I don't use any special line formatting
to cue to reader to its regular metric.

I've got to do something special for Landing Day!

So we get "Brent Baccala's favorite foods in iambic pentameter",
which I think is the single silliest thing in this book!
