T + 150 days    somebody must die

[[
In the first edition, they crashed on their first landing attempt and thus never
landed on Mars.  This was unsatisfactory from a plot standpoint because
there was no good way to explain why some of the crew remained in orbit.
Also, I came to believe that the novel was about 10,000 words too short,
which caused it to read more like a novella at times, like the scene at Andrea's family farm.
Also, Mercuriou's overall motivation was confusing with so little back story.
I had deliberately
kept it short so that people would read it, but now it was too short.

None of these problems seemed fatal; adding a second opening scene
(it used to start with the super-hack) and a landing scene were
straightforward solutions.

So the disaster scene (this chapter) has now become a later landing,
and that makes the plot more believable, that some of them
remain in orbit.
]]

Four landings later, Burns and Vic were on the ground unloading supplies
from the 767 as the remaining crew worked in orbit to stage additional cargo
for the next landing.

