Andrea: "This is what Alister recorded on the high-speed film."

The video showed the doomed 767 in high definition, seen from almost
directly above, buffeted in slow motion by hurricane force winds.

Andrea: "NASA's been able to enhance it to show the eddies."

The video now showed strong vortices coming off of the running
engines, enlarging and growing, twisting and coalescing into a single
massive storm.  Andrea let it play through the breakup sequence.

Andrea: "We've estimated the decent path of the cockpit, but there's
no reason to think that anybody's still alive or that we
have any kind of viable ground rescue option."

The video played on, now showing only the storm slowly dissipating and
disappearing like a voodoo phantom conjured by a pagan priestess.

Andrea: "We just don't know what happened.  The engines obviously
interacted somehow with the storm, but nothing in any of our Martian
atmospheric models predicts anything like it."

Mercuriou said nothing.

Andrea: "Here's our flight plan."

Mercuriou took the tablet she offered him and looked at it briefly.

Mercuriou: "What the hell is this?"

Andrea: "It's our way home."

Andrea: "We can barely move right now.  We've got spare engines in storage.  We can move an engine to the
tail, but it'll take us a month to move it and another month to hook it up,
and that's if we work like crazy.  We can't do it in time.
We'll have to go around a full synodic orbit."

[[
In my imagination, they've somehow got fuel, oxygen, water, electricity fed throughout
the ship.  I guess a spacewalk (or five) is required, but I'm trying to keep this
novel rather short, and describing a spacewalk in detail has already been done
in the first chapter.
]]

Mercuriou met her with a blank stare.

Mercuriou: "That'll take two years."

Andrea: "More like a year and a half."

[[
Mars' synodic period is actually just over two years, but I need this return voyage to take
a year and a half to fit 9/11 and the _Columbia_ disaster into the timeline where I want them.
