scientific evidence.  That's a lot like the evidence
for God's existence.  Consider something like the Miracle
of the Sun in 1917.  
Consider what happened in Fatima, Portugal in 1917.
Three eight-year-old kids said
they saw a beautiful woman who claimed to be
Mary, the mother of Jesus, and who told them that
she would work a miracle with the Sun in six months
time.  On that day, six months hence, in October 1917, thirty or forty
thousand people witnessed the Sun change colors,
move around in the sky, and appear to spin on its axis!"

ARM: "Well if all those thousands of people were staring
at the Sun, who knows what they might have imagined
to have seen?  It was probably some kind of mass hallucination!
What else are we to believe?  That
the Sun and the Earth were ripped out of their orbits in some way?"

[[
I didn't know much at all about the miracle of the Sun until
I read _The_God_Delusion_.  Dawkins' book really disappointed
me, too.  I was hoping he would make a solid case for atheism,
and I really wanted to read it, but his argument is so full
