T + 393 days    it must be strange

[[
Andrea's dream about Alaska.  Why is it here?  Because the political
program proposed for Hawai'i could just as easily work in Alaska.
That's it.  That's all.  That's what this chapter "means".

Like most writing, it's
semi-autobiographical.  Of course I did most of that!  How
else could I have written about it in such detail?  My
imagination isn't that good.
]]

"Dr. Yeats?"

Andrea looked up from the airline magazine she was reading.

Andrea: "Yes?"

"Would you like to visit the flight deck?"

Andrea: __Kyle__! "I'd love to!"

Andrea unfastened her seatbelt and followed the flight attendant to
the jetliner's cockpit, where a warm welcome greated her.
She shook the hands of both pilots, then settled into the jump seat,
fell silent, and started gazing out the window at
the night sky, which was starting to glow red across the horizon to the plane's right.
The pilots engaged in some radio chatter.

[[
First, she thought Kyle Lankier had invited her forward,
then he's never mentioned again.  This is deliberate;
it's a dream, and she's forgotten all about him a moment later.
]]

"Oceanic clearance via waypoints TIN CITY, NORTHWAY, ICE POOL, SIVUQAQ, then direct ANCHORAGE."

[[
Believe it or not, these are all actual aviation waypoint names
in Alaska, but they're scattered all over the place.
I especially like having a native village right before Anchorage,
so I picked Sivuqaq because I've been there on a mission trip
to help the village build a new church.  It's on St. Lawrence
Island, 35 miles from the Russian coast, and, proximity
to land notwithstanding, is the most remote community I've ever
been to in my life.

"Oceanic clearance" because I imagine the flight coming from Hawaii.
]]

By five am, Andrea was walking along the airport's
glass windowed concourse, marveling at the sun now 30 degrees above the horizon.
Then came her connecting flight.  As she deplaned again,
she saw a priest greeting another man.  Was there a connection?

[[
Q: How can it be 30 degrees above the horizon a half hour after sunrise?
A: it's a dream

Yet in Alaska, it can sure be well above the horizon by five am.

The priests were real; I saw them the first time I deplained in Juneau.
I should have to walked over and introduced
myself, but they were total strangers, so I walked on.  I would
have liked to have known the one priest better; I did met him eventually,
but he died shortly thereafter.

Take what God gives you.
]]

Somehow she got a ride downtown.  Was there a bus?  The town
was nestled between a mountain and a wide channel of
water.  Trees loomed over everything; there was some kind of tramway.
Metal staircases sometimes took the place of sidewalks.

[[
The first time I arrived in Juneau, I probably hitchhiked
into town from the airport, but I only vaguely remember
the ride.  I don't think I took the bus.

Juneau's between Mount Roberts and the Gastineau Channel,
the Mount Roberts Tramway runs from sea level to
the plateau, and the metal staircases were built
because the town is quite hilly and it ices
up in the winter.
]]

Then it was dinner time and she was at a homeless shelter.

[[
The _Glory_Hole_.  I didn't name it.  The allusion is
to mining, prominent in Alaskan history, not to anything sexual.
]]

"What kind of weird sex thing you trying to pull?  You were siting in there wearing nothing but your panties!"

Andrea: "I don't know what you're talking about!  I just got here!"

"You can get the hell outta here, is what you can do!"

[[
Something like that happened to me.  It wasn't my first night in Juneau,
but maybe within the first week.  I got up on a Sunday morning,
put on a shorts and a T-shirt, walked through an open door with
no sign on it, sat down in a chair and starting reading my Bible.
One of the staff came in and told me I had to leave, that it
was a restricted area.  That night I was thrown out of the
mission by the night manager, who hadn't been there, but
had heard somehow that I was in the staff area in only
my underwear, thus setting in motion all of the events
of Andrea's dream.
]]

Andrea took her bedroll and trudged out into the night.  She followed
a road until the pavement ended, then she was walking over wooden
planks and a bridge over a raging creek and a dirt road that continued up the mountain
until it ended at a clearing with old mining equipment scattered
about and nothing but a trail continued on.  The place was deserted,
so she walked a short way back down the road, then climbed
up the wooded slope and laid down to sleep.

It began to rain, a cold, driving rain, accessory to an already
chilly night.  Soaking wet, she trudged back down to
the bridge and followed a trail that led down alongside the rushing creek.
Eventually she came to a building
that offered some shelter from the rain, and she
settled down in her wet clothes to await the dawn.
The rain kept coming down on her no matter how she sat.
Finally, she dozed off...

[[
It's Basin Road, Perserverance Trail, and Gold Creek in Juneau,
and it all pretty much happened like that.

I kinda messed around with the grammar a bit to try and
make it seem at least a little dream-like.
]]

..and awoke with a start.  She was in her usual sleeping
compartment onboard _Xplorer_One_, but her sleeping bag was
soaking wet and ice cold.  A water line had burst
a leak and slowly inundated her with cold water as she slept.
As she cleaned up the mess, she slowly turned the
strange dream over and over in her mind.

[[
I could drag this description on for a bit, and maybe
I should, but the point of the chapter has been made.
]]


T + 394 days    it must be anti-Semitic

NASA had arranged for the _Xplorer_One_ crew to transfer to the space
shuttle _Columbus_ at the end of a two week scientific mission notable
for including the first Palestinian astronaut, Major Hasan Nass, of
Hamas.  The shuttle commander, Jeff Janders, had know Andrea for
years.

alNass: "Sal\=amu `Alaykum", Nass greeted Mercuriou fervently,
kissing both his cheeks after shaking his hand during introductions,
then helping the _Xplorer_One_ crew stow their personal belongings in the
attached Spacehab.

[[
It's an Arabic greeting.

I hope.
]]

alNass: "You'll be fine in here.  The Spacehab's got the same life
support as the cabin."

[[
Nass is the Arabic word for "people", as in "the people" (alnass)

As Andrea will soon ask, "where did I find this guy"?

Earlier drafts of the novel featured the crew returning via the
International Space Station (still with the same shuttle disaster)
where they met an old friend of Andrea's, the Russian cosmonaut
Borsov, named, if I recall, after the mission commander in Clarke's _Rama_II_.
Borsov was an old school communist who gave us some unapologetic
Marxism to go with his vodka shots and boisterous charm.

(all of this, incidentally, should be in the novel's
version history on github)

At this point, I still planned to interview the _Columbia_'s crew
surviving family to portray them accurately in the novel.  It was
apparant to me that not only was this infeasible, but it might cause problems,
say, if they objected to the actual crew being portrayed in the novel at all.

So I was already working on an alternate ending when the shuttle's
name would be changed and its crew replaced with fictional characters.

What, however, to do with Colonel Ramon?

Replacing the world's first Israeli astronaut with the first world's
Palestinian astronaut seemed most consistent with the overall tone
of the novel.  Borsov got mixed in with Nass and the alternate
ending gradually became the prime ending.

After the events of the last three decades (1990-2020), from the collapse
of the Soviet Union to the War on Terror, how apropos
it now seems to replace a red Bolshevik with a screaming
Islamic fanatic!
]]

Another old friend of Andrea's was payload specialist David Smith, but
he had not greeted her as warmly, and seemed rather aloof.  When they
were alone for a minute, she found out why.

David: "We're not making it back from this mission, Andrea."

Andrea: "What are you talking about?"

David: "I've had dreams... nightmares... burning up in space."

[[
David Smith and Story Musgrave are the only real astronauts,
and in fact the only real people, to appear in the novel.
I do believe I've read that Smith had premonitions of
the _Columbia_ disaster, though I couldn't verify that,
so I decided to include him
and his dreams.
]]

After both crews enjoyed a dinner of rehydrated lobster bisque,
Major Nass sailed over to the galley, opened his personal compartment,
and pulled out two pouches containing two clear liquids.
Somehow, he turned so that the
green, red and black striped flag on his right shoulder seemed more
noticeable than before.

[[
Lobster bisque, I've read, is a food introduced perhaps on the
Apollo missions?  Or maybe it didn't make it into orbit until Skylab,
but I remember reading it was actual 1970s-era astronaut food.

The drink is called arak.  According to wikipedia, it is the traditional
alcoholic beverage in Palestine.
]]

alNass: "Captain, you may live the rest of your life as a dog in an
American kennel, but tonight we celebrate like men."

Nass joined the two drink pouches together and squeezed the one
to inject its contents into the other, which transformed
into a milkey white liquid.
Andrea raised an eyebrow as Nass distributed the liquor
using smaller drink bags filled with ice.

[[
There really is some preparation like this when consuming arak;
see the wikipedia article.  The way I've got it doped out,
you'd have to do something like this to serve arak properly in space.
]]

Andrea: "Just out of curiosity, major, what would be the Muslim
solution to the _Xplorer_One_ theft?"

alNass: "Cut off your hands?"

The Americans guffawed, and Jeff Janders fired back.

Janders: "Most Americans would consider that cruel and unusual punishment."

alNass: "So what if it is?  Is the loss of a hand too great a price
to pay for freedom?  Let's ask the criminal - Captain
Mercuriou, which would you prefer - to lose your hand, no, let's make it
both hands - one for the billion dollar theft and one for getting your friends killed -
both hands off or spend your life in prison!?"

The cabin fell silent as Mercuriou surveyed the surrounding faces.

Mercuriou: "I think I'd give the hands very serious consideration."

Now it was Nass's turn to explode in glee.

alNass: "You see!  And we don't waste our money on so many jails!"

Several of the Americans began to object simultaneously, but Nass
ignored them, appropriated for himself the remaining arak, for that is the
name of the drink, and next produced
a bowl of Hawai'ian "kine"!

[[
Not only another bit of drug use, but another Hawaiian allusion!
]]

alNass: "More to your taste, Captain?"

Mercuriou: "Thank you."

After the space captain has taken his first "hit" in over a year,
he turned back to Nass.

Mercuriou: "I take it you're a fan?"

The Palestinian major sneered.

alNass: "A fan!?  I listened to your speech.  You're still talking
about 'freedom'!"

alNass: "What is your freedom?!  Money, sex, guns!  Get rich on Wall
Street!  Change yourself into a woman!  The most devastating killing
machines ever devised by man, for sale to all of your friends!  Ask
the people of Gaza what 'freedom' has done for them!"

Jeff Janders had trained with Hasan Nass for a year, had endured two weeks
on orbit with the cocky and flamboyant major, had just witnessed him
producing and consuming first alcohol and then marijuana in flight, and was not about to back
down in an argument now.

Janders: "The people of Israel can vote..."

alNass: "The people of Israel can not vote!  With their racist Aliyah,
Israel is as much a democracy as South Carolina was in 1860!  Let
every Jew come back and vote, and let every Arab come back and vote,
too.  Then let's have an election!  Then let's see who wins!
Mercuriou's right.  What does he call it, a 'game show government'?  You
define your majority how you want, then you get your elections how you want, too."

Janders: "We do not define the majority how we want.  The majority is defined by
law."

alNass: "Who wrote the law?  The Jews!  Obviously non-citizens can not
vote.  Clearly the State of Israel can establish its own citizenship
requirements.  You think it's all so cut and dry."

Andrea: "...and what happens if Hamas takes over?  War until
Israel is destroyed?  Then what happens to the Jews?"

The cabin again fell silence as Nass bowed his head and assumed a reverent posture.

alNass: "May the will of Allah be done."

The shuttle commander practically exploded.

Janders: "You call that a prayer!  I'll bet it was real popular in those Christian churches in South Carolina, too!"

alNass: "You own religion is not free from blood, Jeff!  We've been
fighting you Infidels since Urban the Second sent us the first
Crucade!  This war between us has now gone on over a thousand years!"

Andrea: "If your forefathers were seeking Jesus, they would have
been better served to look for Him in the monasteries of Egypt rather
than in the armies landing at Tyre!"

alNass: "The desert lands are ours!  Arabs will rule the desert if takes ten thousand years!"

Andrea: "I'm sorry, what is your party again?"

alNass: "I'm a radical Islamic nationalist, of course!"

[[
There is no such party (that I'm aware of), but an "Islamic nationist" is meant to
sound as self-contradictory as a "communist nationalist",
since communism preaches a global proletarian movement.
]]

Andrea: "But I thought Islam was open to the whole world, not just to Arabs?"

alNass glared at his American nemesis, then looked to the bag of arak,
which was nearly empty.  He bolted down a final slug, then shifted gears.

alNass: "All these people sing your hymns, talk about Jesus, loving
the poor, forgiving their enemies, and then they go to work in a war
factory.  Why?"

Andrea sighed deeply.

Andrea: "I've tried to stay away from war factories, personally."

alNass: "But the people who work there, don't they believe in Jesus?
Aren't they saved?  They're going to heaven, right?"

Andrea paused again.

Andrea: "I don't know.  Not all of them.  Maybe not any of them.  I just don't know."

alNass: "How many people on our side believe in Allah the same way?"

Janders: "What I'd like to know is why are you one of them?"

alNass: "I?  One of them?"

Janders: "Yes, why do you advocate for war?"

alNass: "Advocate for war?  I am here as an emassary of peace!  A symbol of the unity
between the people of the United States of America and those of the Palestinian Authority!
As well as the only man on this spacecraft to welcome this condemned criminal with
a modicum of grace!"

Janders: "Then why do you hate so Jews and infidels?"

alNass: "Because they're finished!  _Finished_!  The Jews
are _finished_!  The third temple must be destroyed!  Islam will rule
again in Jerusalem!"

[[
In Nass's mind, Islam is destined to rule
the world and all non-believers will live under Islamic rule,
which is also conveniently Arab rule.
]]

Andrea leaned close to Janders and whispered in his ear.

Andrea:  "Where did you find this guy?"

The shuttle commander shrugged.

Janders: "Beats me.  They told us he was a moderate."

alNass: "A moderate!  I am a moderate!  If I were a radical, I'd have
C-4 instead of caviar in my flight kit!"

[[
Jews will be offended that I've replaced one of their national heros
with this goofball.  Palestinians will be offended by their portrayal
as screaming Islamic fanatics, with the distinction between radicals
and moderates being only whether or not they endorse terrorism.
Americans will be offended by turning the _Columbia_ tragedy into
a punch line.

I'm not trying to offend anyone!  I'm just trying to give
you a good ending to the novel, and this is the best I could
come up with.

Was _Candide_ offensive?  _The_Satanic_Verses_?  The nature
of satire is to mock opposing philosophies; of course
people find it offensive.  I could pull my punches,
but it wouldn't be as good a read.
]]

T + 395 days    some sick "freedom" must win in the end

On the big island of Hawai'i, the seaside town of Hilo had somehow turned into
ground zero for a revolution.  Disappointed hipsters, turned away at
the razor-wire fence that still sealed off the abandoned launch
facility at South Point, had travelled on up the Hawai'i Belt Road,
cruised past Volcanoes National Park and descended on Hilo,
which until now had been mostly known for having its downtown
devastated by a tsunami forty years before.  Tent camps had sprung up
in the beach parks, surrounded by signs calling for revolution and
independence, while those few European tourists lucky enough to have
reservations at the youth hostel found their vacation wiped out by
Americians debating politics until well after midnight.

It was nearly four o'clock in the morning in Hilo when _Columbus_
whizzed by overhead, now well into its retry phase.  As it burned
through the Pacific sky at 2,600 degrees, three astronauts chatted in
the Spacehab at a cool 72.

Mercuriou: "You know, Andrea, before launch we gathered everyone
together below the nose cone and I gave everyone a chance to propose
a name for this vessel that was to launch us on this great journey!
...Everyone except you, that is!  What would you have called our vessel?
What would have named our mission?"

As she sank deep into thought, _Columbus_ slashed across the California
coastline at Mach 23.  Two time zones swept past in the span of time it
took to ask and answer a question; by the time Andrea spoke, it was six a.m.

Andrea: "_The_Royal_Way_."

[[
Hmmm.  Orbital speed is about 90 minutes per orbit, 24 time zones,
so figure about 4 minutes per time zone.  Did it really take her
eight minutes to answer a question?  Artistic license.
]]

Mecuriou leaned back in his pressure suit and silently contemplated
what she could possibly mean.

Three thousand miles east, NASA's primary landing facility at Cape
Canaveral's Kennedy Spaceflight Center had been transformed into an
armed camp.  What with the usual tight security surrounding a space
shuttle launch or landing, the FBI also being on hand to take one
Marcelious Mercuriou into custody along with diplomatic contingents
from both the South African embassy and the Palestinian Authority.
Security guards holding assault rifles.

Protesters picketed both for and against Mercuriou at a "free speech"
zone ten miles away.  His opponents had adopted an electric bolt
to symbolize their desired punishment for the space captain, while others
held signs that read "MERCURIOU FOR PRESIDENT",
along with "FREE ALISTER", and "SMOKE POT AND READ YOUR BIBLE".

[[
The American government has, in recent years, taken to establishing
"free speech" zones at some distance from major political conventions.

Shouldn't his name be Alistair?

I first thought of a using a noose instead of an electric bolt, but
decided to drop it because of its racial connotations.  About the
only punch I've pulled throughout the novel.

"SMOKE POT AND READ YOUR BIBLE" is a sign that Timothy Shouts
suggested for evangelism, and that I've used myself on occasion.  There's
plenty of pictures of me and the sign on social media from San Jose State's 2012
homecoming.  It's a little bit reminiscent of "BONG HITS 4 JESUS",
and it's here to satirize protests that become a platform
for all kinds of screwball messages.
]]

Meanwhile, in the cockpit, the flight crew was studying a tire
pressure warning as Major Nass took imaginary pistol shots at the
American cities passing below in the brightening dawn.

alNass: "There's an infidel!  Boom! ... There's an infidel!  Boom!"

David Smith shushed him down.

David_alNass_David: "There's a problem..." "What!?" "There's a problem with the _shuttle_!"

[[
Yes!  Finally!  _Shut_up_!
]]

Nass fell silent, his attention now riveted on the drama unfolding before him.

Janders: "Does it look like instrumentation?"

Pilot MeGee checked his avionics console again.

McGee: "No way.  It's solid.  Our left rear tires are blown."

Janders: "Now the left gear is showing a barber pole...  We're getting
a lot of aileron trim, too."

[[
There was no cockpit voice recorder.  I like to imagine that
the flight crew was sharp as a tack and right on top of the situation.
]]

The shuttle lurched to one side as a chunk of the left wing broke off,
then the autopilot recovered.

McGee: "What was that?"

Janders: "Another weird shimmy."

Next the radio crackled to life.

Radio: "_Columbus_, Houston, we see your tire pressure messages and we did
not copy your last."

Janders ignored "CAPCOM", instead pointing to the small yellow lights
that indicated RCS thruster activity.

Janders_McGee_Janders: "How long's that been on?"  "What?"  "That!"

The right yaw light was lit solid.

Back in the Spacehab, Mercuriou had given up.

Mercuriou: "Andrea, what do you mean, _The_Royal_Way_?  What, what does that mean?"

Andrea Yeats looked him straight in the eye.

Andrea: "It's Christ's way."

[[
The allusion is to Andrew van der Bijl, aka Brother Andrew.  In his biography
_God's_Smuggler_, he talks lot about the Royal Way.
]]

Suddenly, the orbiter gave a sickening lurch and a warbling two-tone alarm pierced the air.

Andrea: "That's a Master Alarm!"

She glanced down at her status display.

Andrea: "We've lost hydraulics!"

The g-forces that had pinned them against the wall a moment ago
vanished and the shuttle began to roll and sway as it careened through
the air, uncontrolled now by man or machine.

Mercuriou: "Tight up!", Mercuriou barked.

Mercuriou and Andrea needed only to snap their visors shut to get
"tight", but Alister's gloves were off.  As he started to don his left
glove, he looked up and caught Burns' eye.  The engineer was floating
leisurely in the middle of the Spacehab, dressed in a casual pair of
slacks.  His ubiquitous T-shirt read "DON'T BOTHER".  Vic was there, too.

[[
The _Columbia_ accident investigation board concluded that at least
one of the _Columbia_ crewmembers were not wearing their gloves
during reentry.
]]

Mercuriou: "Vic?!  W-what?  You're..."

Vic: "So are you, Marc."

The orbiter was now swaying wildly up and down in a phugoid motion,
exposing the top of the fuselage to the direct heat of re-entry once
every few seconds.  They heard a loud crash and felt something break
loose from the tail.

Burns: "There was a piece of frozen foam insulation that broke off the ET
during launch... smashed a pretty good hole in the leading edge of the
left wing, right through all that protective heat shielding."

Burns' words were punctuated by a ear-splitting crack, like half a
pound of linguine snapped in half in front of a microphone.  The cabin
pitched to the side as the entire cargo bay ripped away from the
forebody and the access tunnel torn loose from the crew module.  Only
a strip of aluminum skin was left connecting _Columbus_ together.
Then that, too, tore free, and the orbiter had split in two.

The power went out, but they were not long in darkness.  The
forward bulkhead began to glow a deep, ominous red.

Vic: "This is a pretty good way to go, Marc.  Quick, but a bit painful.
Say goodbye to Burns."

[[
Is is "quick, but a bit painful"?  From a spiritual perspective,
it's far quicker than cancer, or diabetes, or AIDS, quicker than
recovering from major brain damage or blinding injury.

Mortals might think it's rather slow to be steamed alive in a spacesuit, though.

NASA seems to think that the trama of the capsule breaking up (think car crash times ten) would kill
before you get steamed alive in a sealed spacesuit until its burns apart.  I don't know.
The pressure suits they wear for reentry might not be that fire-resistant (witness Apollo One),
but I don't think that an actual spacesuit would just "vaporize to ashes".
]]

Mercuriou: "Why?"

Burns: "I wasn't saved."

The bulkhead blazed white, then morphed into a wave of flame that
broke over them, a crushing, foaming ten foot wall of raging red
surf that buried them under an ocean of fire and slammed them onto a bed
of coals.  They were burning, Burning, BURNING!! and then their suits
vaporized to ashes which blew away with the flames and left them
hanging in an azure haze.

[[
An allusion to wiping out on a big wave while surfing, like
when I bungled a moderate-sized wave at
Al'i beach park when I was living in Haleiwa and working on the
novel in 2011.  Found myself slammed onto a bed of sand, fortunately, not coals.
]]

_Columbus_ was gone, replaced with a thousand blazing brushes painting
fire on sky.  Then Burns was gone, too, and they were clothed in white
robes.  Of the shuttle crew, only David remained, and he too was
clothed in white.  Below them lay America, above them space, and above
space blazed a stupendous light.

[[
Why only David remains of the shuttle crew?

Well, all the rest were fictional characters.

It seems approriate that story is bookended by the only two actual
astronauts to appear; Story Musgrave in the novel's first scene
and David Smith here.
]]

Alister: "Wh-what!?  That's it!?"

Mercuriou turned to him as the earth, the sun, the galaxy fell away beneath
them.

%Mercuriou: "This isn't the beginning; this isn't the end.  This is the Great
%Conversation."

Mercuriou: "There is no beginning; there is no end.  This is the Great
Conversation."

[[
Again, as I explained at the start of the novel, the allusion is to Mortimer Adler and the Great Books.
The Great Conversation is the conversation among authors over the centuries.

Is there a beginning to the Great Conversation?  If so, it's been
lost to history; all we have left are those writings that remain extanct.
Is there an end?  Only if humanity itself ceases to exist.

Every generation, every "great" author
adds their own voice and the conversation continues,
and the test of "greatness" is whether you add something
new and significant to the Great Conversation.

I hope it wasn't too confusing.
]]

